  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1748, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$MM Proposition I$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain Modigliani-Miller Proposition I. In a world with no taxes, why does capital structure not affect firm value, and what changes once you bring taxes back in?$x$, $x$["Firm Value Independent Of Financing Mix In Frictionless World", "Financing Only Divides A Fixed Operating Cash-Flow Pie", "Homemade Leverage Arbitrages Away Any Value Gap", "Assumptions: No Taxes, No Distress Costs, Efficient Markets", "Taxes Break It: Interest Tax Shield Adds Value", "MM Is The Baseline That Isolates Which Imperfection Matters"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Modigliani-Miller Proposition I says that with no taxes, no bankruptcy costs, and efficient markets, the total value of a firm is independent of how it is financed - the size of the pie does not change just because you cut it into debt and equity differently. The intuition is that capital structure only divides up a fixed stream of operating cash flows; it does not create or destroy them, so enterprise value is set by the assets, not the financing. If two identical firms had different values purely because of leverage, an investor could use homemade leverage, borrowing or lending on their own account, to arbitrage the gap away, which forces the values back together. So why do we say debt adds value in the real world? Because we relax the assumptions. The biggest one is taxes - interest is tax-deductible, so leverage creates a tax shield that genuinely accrues to the firm. Once you add that, value rises with leverage. MM is not a description of reality; it is the frictionless baseline that tells you which imperfection - taxes, distress, agency, signaling - is actually driving a capital-structure decision.$x$),
(1749, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$MM Proposition II$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Walk me through Modigliani-Miller Proposition II. If debt is cheaper than equity, why does adding leverage not lower WACC in a no-tax world?$x$, $x$["Cost Of Equity Rises Linearly With Debt-To-Equity", "Leverage Concentrates Business Risk On Smaller Equity Base", "Cheaper Debt Exactly Offset By More Expensive Equity", "WACC Constant, Equals Unlevered Cost Of Capital", "Apparent Saving Is An Illusion: Remaining Equity Reprices", "With Taxes, After-Tax Debt Genuinely Lowers WACC Until Distress Bites"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Proposition II is the companion to Proposition I and it explains why your weighted average cost of capital does not fall as you add cheap debt, even though debt looks cheaper than equity. It says the cost of equity rises linearly with the debt-to-equity ratio. The mechanic is that leverage concentrates the same business risk onto a smaller equity base, so equity holders demand a higher return to bear that amplified risk. In the no-tax world the two effects exactly offset: you are adding more low-cost debt, but the equity you still have gets more expensive at precisely the rate that keeps WACC flat. So WACC is constant and equals the unlevered cost of capital regardless of leverage. The practical takeaway is that you cannot lower your cost of capital just by swapping equity for debt in a frictionless world - the apparent saving is an illusion because the remaining equity reprices. Once you introduce the tax shield, debt becomes genuinely cheaper after tax and WACC does decline with leverage, at least until distress and agency costs start to push the cost of both debt and equity back up.$x$),
(1750, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Pecking Order Theory$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What is pecking-order theory, and how does it explain why some of the most profitable companies carry the least debt?$x$, $x$["Driven By Asymmetric Information Between Managers And Investors", "Financing Hierarchy: Internal Funds, Then Debt, Then Equity Last", "Equity Issuance Signals Overvaluation, Pushes Price Down", "Debt Less Information-Sensitive, Weaker Negative Signal", "Leverage Is Residue Of Past Profitability, Not A Target", "Profitable Firms Self-Fund So End Up Low-Levered"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Pecking-order theory comes out of asymmetric information - managers know more about the firm's true value than outside investors do. Because of that, financing follows a strict preference order: internal funds first, then debt, then external equity as a last resort. The logic is signaling. If management issues new equity, the market reasonably suspects they think the stock is overvalued, since no one wants to sell cheap shares, so the announcement itself tends to push the price down. Debt is far less sensitive to that mispricing problem because its payoff is capped and more predictable, so issuing debt sends a weaker negative signal. Retained earnings carry no signal at all. The big implication is that capital structure is not chosen to hit some clean optimal leverage target - it is the cumulative residue of past profitability and financing needs. Highly profitable firms end up with low leverage simply because they funded themselves internally and never needed to borrow, which is the opposite of what a pure tax-shield trade-off model would predict. In practice I treat pecking order and trade-off theory as complements, not rivals.$x$),
(1751, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Distress And Agency Costs$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Beyond the tax shield, what are the costs that make more debt destroy value? Walk me through the costs of financial distress and the agency costs of debt.$x$, $x$["Direct Distress Costs: Legal And Advisory Fees", "Indirect Costs Larger: Lost Customers, Suppliers, Staff, Distraction", "Agency Cost Is Shareholder-Creditor Conflict At High Leverage", "Risk-Shifting / Asset Substitution: Equity Takes Bets, Creditors Eat Downside", "Debt Overhang: Good Projects Skipped Because Gains Leak To Creditors", "Creditors Price It In Via Spreads And Covenants; Creates Interior Optimum"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Once you go past the point where the tax shield dominates, two real costs start eating the value leverage creates. The first is financial distress. Direct costs are the legal and advisory fees of a restructuring, but the indirect costs are usually larger and bite well before any filing - customers worry about warranties and walk, suppliers tighten terms, key staff leave, and management fights fires instead of running the business. The second is the agency cost of debt, the conflict between shareholders and creditors at high leverage. Two classic behaviors: risk-shifting, or asset substitution, where equity holders take wild bets because they capture the upside while creditors eat the downside; and debt overhang, where so much value accrues to existing creditors that shareholders rationally pass up good projects because the gains leak to lenders. Creditors anticipate all of this and price it in through higher spreads and tighter covenants. Together, distress and agency costs are the downward-sloping side of the trade-off - they are why the marginal value of leverage eventually turns negative and there is an interior optimum.$x$),
(1752, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Sizing Debt To A Rating$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A 500 million EBITDA industrial wants to lever up but defend a solid BBB rating. How do you size its debt capacity, and how does a higher-for-longer rate environment change your answer?$x$, $x$["Anchor To Agency Leverage And Coverage Thresholds For The Rating", "BBB Industrial Roughly Low-To-Mid 2x Debt-To-EBITDA, Sector-Dependent", "Cross-Check Interest Coverage At A Stressed Rate, Not Spot", "Haircut For Cyclicality: Size To Trough EBITDA", "Leave Headroom For M&A, Buybacks, A Bad Year", "Higher-For-Longer: Refi At Higher Coupon Can Breach Coverage"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would size the debt so the pro-forma credit metrics land squarely inside the agency thresholds for the rating we want to defend, with a cushion. With 500 million of EBITDA and a target of a solid BBB, the agencies care most about gross leverage and coverage, so I start from the leverage ratio the rating implies - for a BBB industrial that might be somewhere around the low-to-mid 2s times debt-to-EBITDA, though it varies a lot by sector and business risk. At 2.5 times that is 1.25 billion of total debt capacity. Then I sanity-check it against interest coverage - EBITDA or EBIT over interest - to make sure it clears the rating's coverage band at a stressed rate, not just today's rate. I would also haircut for cyclicality: if EBITDA can fall 20 percent in a downturn, I size to the trough so I do not breach mid-cycle. Critically, I do not run right to the edge of the rating - I leave headroom for acquisitions, buybacks, and a bad year. And I would pressure-test it in a higher-for-longer world, because refinancing that debt at a higher coupon can blow through the coverage threshold even if leverage looks fine.$x$),
(1753, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Cash-Flow Debt Capacity$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Instead of an EBITDA multiple, size a company's debt capacity off its cash-flow coverage. Walk me through how you get there and why coverage can be the better lens than a leverage multiple.$x$, $x$["Start From Through-Cycle FCF Before Financing", "FCF = EBITDA Less Cash Taxes, Maintenance Capex, Working Capital", "Set A Target Fixed-Charge Coverage With A Margin", "Coverage Plus All-In Coupon Backs Into Sustainable Debt Service And Principal", "Multiples Ignore Capital Intensity And Actual Coupon", "Stress At Trough Cash Flow And A Refinanced Higher Rate"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Cash-flow coverage sizing flips the question from how much can I borrow on the balance sheet to how much debt service the cash flow can actually carry. I start with a sustainable, through-cycle free cash flow before financing - EBITDA less cash taxes, less maintenance capex, less the working capital the business needs to fund. Then I ask what fixed-charge coverage I want to hold - say I insist this cash flow covers interest plus required amortization at least, hypothetically, two times over for a margin of error. That coverage target, combined with the all-in cost of debt, backs into a sustainable debt service, and from there a principal amount. I anchor on cash flow rather than an EBITDA multiple because multiples ignore capital intensity and the actual coupon - a capex-heavy business, or one borrowing at a higher-for-longer rate, can service far less debt per turn of EBITDA. I would stress the coverage at trough cash flow and at a refinanced higher rate, because a structure that covers comfortably today can fall below one-times fixed charges if rates reset against you at the maturity wall.$x$),
(1754, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Leveraging Recap Signal$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A mature company announces a debt-funded special dividend - a leveraging recapitalization. What does this signal to the market, and when does that signal backfire?$x$, $x$["Debt Funds A Special Dividend Or Large Buyback", "Generally Read As A Positive Signal, Reaction Beyond Mechanics", "Commitment: Fixed Charges Bond Management To Generate Cash, Disciplining Debt", "Confidence: Board Levers Only If Through-Cycle Cash Flows Stable And Durable", "Opposite Of Negative Equity-Issuance Signal Under Pecking Order", "Backfires If Leverage Too Aggressive For Cyclicality Or Rate Regime"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A leveraging recapitalization - issuing a big slug of debt to fund a special dividend or large buyback - tends to be read as a positive signal, and the share price often reacts beyond the mechanical effect. The signaling content runs on a few channels. First, commitment: by locking in fixed interest and amortization, management bonds itself to generate the cash to service that debt, a credible promise to stop empire-building and run leanly - the disciplining-debt argument. Second, confidence in cash flows: a board only piles on permanent leverage if it believes through-cycle cash generation is stable and durable, so the recap signals conviction in the earnings base. Third, there is a genuine tax-shield gain. Note a buyback also says management thinks the equity is cheap, whereas a special dividend does not. The flip side is that the same signal can be misread or simply wrong - if the leverage is too aggressive for the cyclicality of the business, the market sees fragility rather than confidence, especially in a higher-rate world where the interest burden is heavier and refinancing risk is real.$x$),
(1755, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Convertibles And Hybrids$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$When would you reach for a convertible or a hybrid instead of straight debt or straight equity as a capital-structure tool, and what are the trade-offs?$x$, $x$["Convertible Is Debt Plus Embedded Equity Call, Lower Coupon", "Sells Equity At A Premium, Less Immediately Dilutive Than Follow-On", "Suits Growth Or High-Volatility Issuers; Coupon Saving Valuable At High Rates", "Hybrids Earn Partial Equity Credit While Coupon Stays Tax-Deductible", "Hybrids Help Defend A Target Rating Without Full Leverage Hit", "Trade-Offs: Conversion Dilution, Complexity, Expense, Clawed-Back Equity Credit"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Convertibles and hybrids are useful precisely when straight debt or straight equity each have a drawback you want to soften. A convertible bond is debt with an embedded equity call - it carries a lower coupon than straight debt because investors pay for the option, and it lets you sell equity synthetically at a premium to today's price, so it is less immediately dilutive than a follow-on. That suits growth or higher-volatility issuers, and in a higher-for-longer world the coupon saving versus straight high-yield is especially valuable. Hybrids - perpetual or deeply subordinated notes - earn partial equity credit from the rating agencies while the coupon stays tax-deductible, so they add financing without fully loading rating-agency leverage, which helps defend a target rating. The trade-offs are real: convertibles dilute if the stock runs through the strike and bring accounting complexity; hybrids are expensive, the equity credit can be clawed back if terms are wrong, and call or step-up features create their own refinancing dynamics. I treat both as tools to fine-tune the structure at the margin, not a core funding base.$x$),
(1756, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Risk-Free Rate Selection$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$When you build a cost of equity in CAPM, which risk-free rate do you plug in, the three-month T-bill or a long-dated government bond? Walk me through the reasoning and where it actually moves the answer.$x$, $x$["Match Risk-Free Rate To Cash Flow Duration", "DCF Runs To Long Terminal Value, So Use Long Bond", "Ten Or Twenty Year Government Bond, Cash Flow Currency", "Bill Only Prices Three Months Of Inflation And Real-Rate Risk", "Pair Same Long Rate With The Equity Risk Premium Used", "Strip Sovereign Default Risk If Government Not Truly Risk-Free", "Half-Point Rate Difference Compounds Hard In Terminal Value"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The first instinct is to grab a three-month T-bill because it is the cleanest risk-free instrument, but that is usually wrong for a DCF. The risk-free rate in CAPM should be matched to the duration of the cash flows you are discounting, and a DCF runs out to a long-dated terminal value, so I anchor to a long-term government bond, a ten or twenty year, in the currency of the cash flows. The maturity-matching logic is that the bill only compensates for three months of expected inflation and real-rate risk, whereas the cash flows span decades. Mechanically it matters: if the bill is at 4 and the long bond at 4.5, with a beta of 1.2 and a 5 percent equity premium, the cost of equity moves from 10 to 10.5, and that half point compounds heavily in the terminal value. Two consistency points: use the same long rate inside the equity premium you pair with it, do not splice a bill-based premium onto a bond yield, and use a local-currency government bond stripped of default risk if the sovereign is not truly risk-free.$x$),
(1757, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Marginal Cost And Break Point$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Explain what the marginal cost of capital schedule is and how you locate the break point. A company can retain 60 million of earnings and targets a 40 percent equity weight; show me where its WACC steps up and how you would use that schedule.$x$, $x$["Marginal Cost Of Capital = Cost Of Next Dollar Raised", "Rises In Steps As Cheaper Sources Are Exhausted", "Break Point When Retained Earnings Run Out, New Equity Needed", "Break Point = Cheaper Funds Divided By Its Target Weight", "60 Over 0.4 = 150 Million Total New Capital", "New Equity Adds Flotation Cost, Lifts Cost Of Equity And WACC", "Rank Projects By IRR Against Rising Schedule, Cross With IOS"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The marginal cost of capital is the cost of the next dollar of new capital, and it rises in steps as a firm exhausts its cheaper sources. The key step is the break point, where internally generated equity runs out and the firm must issue new shares, which carry flotation costs and so a higher cost of equity. You find the break point by taking the funds available from that cheaper source and dividing by its target weight in the structure. Say a company retains 60 million of earnings and targets 40 percent equity: the break point is 60 divided by 0.4, so 150 million of total new capital. Below 150 the firm funds equity from retained earnings at, say, 11 percent; above it new equity costs 12.5, so the WACC steps up. You then rank projects by IRR against this rising marginal cost schedule, and the optimal budget is where the investment opportunity schedule crosses the marginal cost of capital.$x$),
(1758, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Target Vs Current Weights$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$When you build a WACC, should the debt and equity weights reflect the company's current capital structure or its target? A firm sits at 20 percent debt today but has told the market it will move toward 40 percent. How do you handle it?$x$, $x$["Use Target Weights, Not Today's Snapshot", "WACC Discounts The Whole Forecast And Perpetuity", "Weights Should Reflect Mix Maintained Over That Horizon", "Using 20 Percent Overstates WACC, Undervalues Firm", "Target From Stated Policy, Long-Run History, Or Peers", "Re-Lever Beta And Set Credit Spread To The Same Target", "Weights, Beta And Spread Must Tell One Leverage Story"]$x$::jsonb, $x$You should weight WACC with the target capital structure, not today's snapshot. WACC discounts cash flows over the whole forecast and into perpetuity, so the weights should reflect the financing mix the company will realistically maintain over that horizon, not a temporary position. If a firm is currently 20 percent debt but management has stated it will lever up to roughly 40 percent, using 20 understates the debt benefit and overstates the cost of capital, undervaluing the business. The target is usually drawn from the firm's stated policy, its long-run history, or where comparable companies in the sector sit. One caution: the cost of equity and the cost of debt must both reflect that target leverage too, so you re-lever beta to the target debt-to-equity and use a credit spread consistent with the target rating. Weights, beta and spread all have to tell the same leverage story, otherwise the WACC is internally inconsistent.$x$),
(1759, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Hurdle Rate Under De-Levering$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A corporate funds an acquisition heavily with debt, runs at about 50 percent debt-to-value early, then sweeps cash and de-levers toward 25 percent as it approaches a refinancing wall. Why does a single WACC misprice this, and what would you do instead?$x$, $x$["Single WACC Assumes A Constant Debt-To-Value Ratio", "Breaks When Leverage Moves Across The Forecast", "Overstates Tax Shield In De-Levered Later Years", "Understates Cost Of Equity In Highly Levered Early Years", "Option One: Re-Estimate WACC Year By Year, Re-Lever Beta", "Option Two: APV, Add PV Of Tax Shields Off Scheduled Debt", "APV Natural Because It Drops The Fixed-Ratio Assumption"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A single WACC assumes a constant debt-to-value ratio, so it quietly breaks when leverage moves materially across the forecast. Picture a corporate that funds an acquisition with debt, runs at 50 percent debt-to-value early, then sweeps cash and de-levers toward 25 by the time it hits a refinancing wall. A constant WACC overstates the tax shield in the de-levered later years and understates the cost of equity in the highly levered early ones, so it misprices the cash flows in both directions. You have a few honest options. You can re-estimate WACC year by year, re-levering beta and resetting the debt weight to each period's structure, then discount with the matching annual rate. Cleaner is adjusted present value: value the business unlevered, then add the present value of the tax shields explicitly off the actual scheduled debt balances. APV is the natural tool precisely because it does not assume a fixed ratio, which is the assumption the changing leverage violates.$x$),
(1760, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Currency Of The Discount Rate$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A euro-based parent is evaluating a greenfield project in India. Walk me through the two consistent ways to set the discount rate, the rule you must never break, and how you would actually build the foreign-currency cost of capital.$x$, $x$["Consistency Rule: Discount Rate Currency Matches Cash Flow Currency", "Route One: Rupee Cash Flows At A Rupee Cost Of Capital", "Route Two: Convert To Euros At Forwards, Discount At Euro Rate", "Never Mix Rupee Cash Flows Against A Euro WACC", "Build Local Rate Via Inflation Differential Or Local Risk-Free", "Layer In A Country Risk Premium For Sovereign And Political Risk", "Forward Route Cleaner, Avoids Double-Counting Inflation"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The golden rule is consistency: the discount rate must be denominated in the same currency as the cash flows. If a euro-based parent evaluates a project in India, you either keep the cash flows in rupees and discount at a rupee cost of capital, or convert the cash flows to euros using forward rates and discount at a euro rate. You must never mix, say rupee cash flows against a euro WACC, because that silently bakes in a currency view. To build the local rate you start from a local risk-free rate, or take your home cost of capital and adjust for the inflation differential between the two economies, and you layer in a country risk premium for the sovereign and political risk the project actually bears. The forward-rate route is internally cleaner because covered interest parity already embeds the rate differential, so you avoid double-counting inflation in both the cash flows and the discount rate. Whichever you pick, do it once and apply it consistently.$x$),
(1761, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$WACC Circularity$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$There is a circularity in WACC: the weights depend on the firm's value, but the value depends on the WACC. How do you resolve that in practice, and while you are at it, why do we insist on market-value weights rather than book?$x$, $x$["Circular: Market-Value Weights Depend On Value, Value Depends On WACC", "Resolve By Iterating To Convergence Or Anchoring To Target Structure", "Market Value Is What Investors Could Sell Claims For Today", "Required Return Is On Market Value, Not Historic Book Cost", "Book Equity Stale Or Negative After Buybacks; Book Misses Bond Pricing", "Book Weights Understate Equity Proportion, Distort The Blend", "Default To Target Market-Value Weights, Iterate Only For Precision"]$x$::jsonb, $x$WACC is circular because the weights are based on market values, equity value depends on the discounted cash flows, and those cash flows are discounted at the WACC you are trying to compute. You break the loop either by iterating, guessing a WACC, valuing the firm, re-reading the implied weights and repeating until it converges, or more practically by anchoring to a stable target capital structure so the weights stop moving. On why market values rather than book: WACC is the return investors require on what they could sell their claims for today, not what those claims were recorded at historically. Book equity can be wildly stale or even negative after buybacks, while book debt misses where bonds actually trade. Using book weights would understate the equity proportion for most healthy companies, since market equity usually sits well above book, and that distorts the blend. So market-value weights for the target structure, with iteration only if you need the precision.$x$),
(1762, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Capital Allocation Framework$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$A mature industrial business is generating more cash than it needs to run day to day. Walk me through the capital-allocation framework a CFO should use to decide what to do with that cash, and tell me how return on invested capital helps you rank the options.$x$, $x$["Five uses: reinvest, M&A, pay down debt, dividends, buybacks", "Rank by return on capital versus cost of capital", "Organic reinvestment first when project ROIC beats WACC", "M&A only if returns clear the hurdle after synergies and premium", "Deleverage if over-levered or rates are high", "Return cash only when no internal use beats the hurdle", "Buybacks make sense mainly when shares trade below intrinsic value"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would frame it as a waterfall ranked by return on invested capital against the cost of capital. The first call on cash is organic reinvestment - capex, R and D, working capital - wherever a project earns an ROIC comfortably above WACC, because thats the highest-conviction value creation and it compounds. Next is M and A, but only if the deal clears the hurdle after you account for the control premium and credibly underwrite synergies; most deals destroy value precisely because the price erodes the return. Third, if the balance sheet is over-levered or rates are high, paying down debt is a clean, certain, risk-reducing use. Only once youve exhausted uses that beat the hurdle do you return cash to shareholders. Between dividends and buybacks, dividends suit a stable, predictable payout, while buybacks make sense mainly when the stock trades below your estimate of intrinsic value. The discipline is that returning cash is the residual - its what you do when you cannot reinvest above your cost of capital, not a goal in itself.$x$),
(1763, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Buyback Execution Methods$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$A board has approved a sizable repurchase authorization. Compare the main ways to actually execute it - open-market repurchases under a 10b5-1 plan, an accelerated share repurchase, and a Dutch-auction tender offer - and tell me when you would steer the company toward each.$x$, $x$["Open-market: flexible, drip-fed, no commitment to complete", "10b5-1 plan gives an affirmative defense, trades through blackouts", "ASR: large upfront block via a bank, most shares retired immediately", "ASR final price settles on VWAP over the term", "Dutch auction: holders tender in a price range, clears at lowest clearing price", "Tender retires a large stake fast, usually at a premium", "Choose by speed, signaling, flexibility, and price discipline"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Open-market repurchases are the default - the company buys in the open market over time, usually under a 10b5-1 plan, which is a pre-set trading instruction that gives an affirmative defense against insider-trading claims and lets you keep buying through blackout windows. Its flexible and cheap, you can dial it up or down, but its slow and theres no commitment to finish. An accelerated share repurchase is for speed and signal: you pay a bank a large lump sum upfront, receive most of the shares immediately so EPS and the share count move now, and the final price trues up to the volume-weighted average over the ASR term. You use it when you want an immediate, credible reduction in shares and are confident in the value. A Dutch-auction tender lets holders state the price within a range at which theyll sell, and you buy at the single lowest price that clears the desired volume - good for retiring a big block quickly, often at a modest premium, while imposing price discipline. So I steer by speed, signaling intent, flexibility, and how much I care about the price paid.$x$),
(1764, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Accretion Versus Value$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A company earning 100 of net income on 100 million shares trades at 15 times earnings. It funds a 150 buyback with debt at 5 percent pre-tax, 25 percent tax rate. Show me the EPS impact, and then explain why analysts who cheer the accretion are confusing it with value creation.$x$, $x$["EPS0 is 1.00; buy 10m shares at 15 to reach 90m shares", "After-tax interest 150 x 5% x 0.75 equals about 5.6", "New EPS about 1.05, roughly 5 percent accretive", "Accretive whenever earnings yield exceeds after-tax cost of debt", "Earnings yield 6.7% beats after-tax cost 3.75%", "Accretion says nothing about price versus intrinsic value", "Adds financial leverage and risk; a math identity, not value"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The mechanics first. EPS starts at 100 over 100 million, so a dollar. At 15 a share, 150 of buyback retires 10 million shares, leaving 90 million. The debt costs 150 times 5 percent times one-minus-25-percent, about 5.6 of after-tax interest, so net income falls to roughly 94.4. Divide by 90 million and EPS is about 1.05 - call it 5 percent accretive. Heres the trap: a debt-funded buyback is EPS-accretive whenever the earnings yield, here one over 15 or 6.7 percent, exceeds the after-tax cost of debt, here 3.75 percent. That condition is met by almost any company at almost any time, so accretion is nearly automatic and tells you essentially nothing. What it ignores is price versus intrinsic value - youve created value only if you bought shares below what theyre worth, regardless of the EPS optics. And youve swapped equity for debt, so youve levered the equity and raised its risk; a higher EPS on a riskier earnings stream isnt worth more per unit. Accretion is an arithmetic identity, not evidence of value creation.$x$),
(1765, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Buybacks Destroying Value$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Buybacks are sometimes described as a transfer of value between selling and continuing shareholders. Using a company you believe is worth 20 a share but trading at 25, show me what a repurchase does to continuing holders, and lay out the two classic ways buybacks destroy value.$x$, $x$["Buyback above intrinsic value transfers value to sellers", "Worth 20, buy 20% at 25: intrinsic per share falls to 18.75", "Buying at a discount reverses it, lifting per-share value to 21.25", "Destroyer one: repurchasing overvalued shares at a peak", "Destroyer two: debt-funded buybacks at the top of the cycle", "Pro-cyclical buying high, cutting when cheap in a downturn", "Higher-for-longer rates raise the bar on debt-funded repurchase"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Think of intrinsic value as a fixed pie shared by the shares outstanding. If the equity is worth 2000 - 20 a share on 100 shares - and you spend 500 buying 20 shares at the 25 market price, you hand 500 of real cash out the door but only retire shares worth 400 of intrinsic value. The remaining intrinsic equity is 1500 over 80 shares, so per-share value drops from 20 to 18.75. Youve transferred value from the continuing holders to the ones who sold at an inflated price. Buy the same shares at 15 instead and the math reverses - per-share value rises to 21.25. So the first way buybacks destroy value is repurchasing overvalued stock; management is supposed to be the disciplined buyer, yet companies notoriously buy most heavily when the stock and their own confidence are highest. The second is funding those peak-price buybacks with debt, loading leverage onto the balance sheet exactly when the cycle is most stretched, then forcing a halt - or worse, a raise - when the stock is cheap in the downturn. Pro-cyclical buying high and stopping low is the classic destroyer, and with rates higher-for-longer the debt-funded version is even harder to justify.$x$),
(1766, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Dividend Policy Theory$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$In a frictionless world dividend policy is irrelevant, yet boards agonize over it. Walk me through the signaling, clientele, and residual theories of dividend policy, and explain why companies work so hard to keep the dividend stable rather than letting it swing with earnings.$x$, $x$["Miller-Modigliani: policy irrelevant without taxes and frictions", "Signaling: initiations and increases signal confidence in durable cash flow", "Cuts are punished far harder than the cash involved", "Clientele: the investor base self-selects by payout and tax preference", "Residual: pay out only what beating-the-hurdle reinvestment leaves over", "Stability and smoothing because the board defends the dividend (Lintner)", "Sticky dividend means raise only when sure it is sustainable"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Start from Miller-Modigliani: with no taxes or frictions, a dollar paid as a dividend just lowers the share price by a dollar, so policy is irrelevant - investors can make their own dividends by selling. Frictions are why it matters in practice. Signaling theory says that because managers know more than the market, raising or initiating a dividend is a costly, credible signal that they expect cash flows to be durable, while a cut screams distress, which is why cuts get punished far harder than the cash involved. Clientele theory says investors self-select - income-seekers and certain tax profiles gravitate to high payers, growth investors to low or none - so changing policy abruptly alienates your base. Residual theory is the disciplined view: fund every reinvestment that beats the hurdle first, then pay out whats left, which would make dividends lumpy. Companies dont do that, and thats the point about stability - boards smooth dividends, raising only when confident the new level is sustainable, because the market treats the dividend as a near-promise. That stickiness, the Lintner insight, is why a stable, slowly growing dividend is prized over one that tracks earnings.$x$),
(1767, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Special Dividend Vs Recap$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A profitable, lightly levered company has built up a large slug of cash from an asset sale and wants to return it. The board is weighing a one-time special dividend, a buyback, and a leveraged recapitalization. Walk me through the trade-offs and how you would advise them.$x$, $x$["Special dividend: fast, pro-rata, no ongoing commitment, hits all holders", "Buyback benefits continuing holders, and only if priced below intrinsic value", "Recap layers on debt to fund a larger distribution, changing capital structure", "Recap adds a tax shield but also fixed charges and financial risk", "One-time cash avoids setting a permanent dividend expectation", "Signaling: a recap signals confidence in cash flow to service debt", "Match the tool to valuation, leverage capacity, and investor base"]$x$::jsonb, $x$These differ on who benefits, whether you add leverage, and what expectation you set. A special dividend is the cleanest way to return a one-time windfall: its fast, pro-rata so every holder gets cash, and explicitly labeled special, so it doesnt set a permanent payout expectation the way raising the regular dividend would. A buyback returns the same cash but selectively - it benefits the holders who stay, and only creates value if youre buying below intrinsic value, so Id favor it only if the stock looked cheap. A leveraged recap is different: you raise debt to fund a much larger distribution, deliberately moving the capital structure toward a more optimal mix. That captures an interest tax shield and can lift returns on the remaining equity, but it loads on fixed charges and risk and only works if cash flows are stable enough to service the debt - which is itself a confidence signal. My advice turns on three things: is the stock under or overvalued, how much spare debt capacity exists given where rates are, and what the investor base wants. If the company is genuinely under-levered with steady cash flows and the equity isnt cheap, a modest recap funding a special dividend is often most efficient; if the stock is clearly undervalued, lean to the buyback; if they just want to hand back a windfall simply, the special dividend wins.$x$),
(1768, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Returns Versus Growth Capex$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A large-cap with a long buyback track record is now facing a surge in AI and growth capex that competes for the same cash. The board asks whether to protect the buyback or redirect cash to investment. How do you frame that decision, and what would tip you each way?$x$, $x$["Compare marginal ROIC on capex versus value from buyback at the current price", "Reinvestment wins if incremental returns credibly beat WACC", "Buyback wins mainly when shares trade below intrinsic value", "Higher-for-longer rates raise the hurdle for both uses", "Avoid underinvesting to defend an EPS or buyback optic", "Weigh option value and competitive necessity of AI capex", "Preserve flexibility; do not debt-fund buybacks to protect the optic"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I frame it as a head-to-head on returns, not as defending a habit. On one side is the marginal ROIC on the incremental AI and growth capex; on the other is the value created by buying back stock at todays price, which is only positive if the shares trade below intrinsic value. Whichever clears the cost of capital by more wins the marginal dollar. What tips me toward reinvestment is credible evidence that the incremental projects earn well above WACC, plus the competitive reality that AI capacity can be table stakes - underinvesting to protect an EPS or buyback optic is exactly the value-destruction trap, sacrificing the franchise for a near-term number. What tips me toward the buyback is a genuinely cheap stock and a thin pipeline of investments that beat the hurdle. The rate environment matters on both sides: higher-for-longer lifts the cost of capital, so it raises the bar for the capex and makes overpaying for your own shares costlier too. The discipline I would press on the board is to size capex to the opportunities that actually clear the hurdle, fund those first, return whats genuinely residual, and not lever up to keep the buyback intact just to defend the optics.$x$),
(1769, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Debt-Funded Buyback Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company near the top of its cycle wants to fund a large buyback with new debt, and it already has a meaningful maturity wall coming due in 2028. The CEO points to the EPS accretion. Talk me through the risks you would raise with the board before signing off.$x$, $x$["Accretion is automatic when earnings yield beats after-tax cost of debt", "Pro-cyclical risk: buying own shares at a peak valuation", "Adds leverage into a 2028 refinancing wall at higher rates", "Refinancing risk: maturing debt reprices up, lifting the interest burden", "Erodes the equity cushion and covenant/ratings headroom in a downturn", "May be forced to halt buybacks or issue equity when the stock is cheap", "Recommend staging, preserving liquidity, and pre-funding the wall"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Id start by deflating the EPS argument: a debt-funded buyback is accretive almost automatically, whenever the earnings yield exceeds the after-tax cost of debt, so the accretion the CEO points to is an arithmetic certainty, not evidence the trade is wise. Then Id lay out the real risks. First, valuation timing - buying back stock near a cyclical peak risks paying above intrinsic value and transferring value to the holders who sell. Second, and more pressing, youre adding leverage right into a 2028 maturity wall. With rates higher-for-longer, that maturing debt very likely refinances at a meaningfully higher coupon, so youre raising the interest burden into a known refinancing event and stacking fresh debt on top. Third, the buyback shrinks the equity cushion exactly when you want more flexibility - it eats into covenant and ratings headroom, so if the cycle turns youre squeezed on two fronts. The cruel irony is that a stressed, over-levered company is forced to stop buying, or even issue equity, when the stock is cheapest - the opposite of disciplined capital allocation. Id recommend staging the repurchase, protecting liquidity, and addressing or pre-funding the 2028 wall before committing debt capacity to buying shares at the top.$x$),
(1770, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$NPV Versus IRR$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$If NPV and IRR rank two mutually exclusive projects differently, which do you trust and why? And explain what the reinvestment-rate assumption has to do with it.$x$, $x$["NPV Is The Decision Rule, Maximizes Dollar Value", "IRR Is A Percentage, Ignores Scale", "Conflict Arises With Mutually Exclusive Projects", "NPV Assumes Reinvestment At WACC, IRR At The IRR", "IRR Reinvestment Assumption Often Unrealistic And Too Optimistic", "Independent Projects Usually Agree If Conventional Cash Flows", "Pick The Positive-NPV, Higher-NPV Project"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I trust NPV. NPV measures the actual dollars of value a project adds at the cost of capital, and our job is to maximize value, so the higher-NPV project wins when they are mutually exclusive and we can only pick one. IRR is just a rate, and it ignores scale. A small project can post a gorgeous IRR but add far less value than a bigger project with a lower IRR. The conflict usually comes from differences in size or in the timing of cash flows. The reinvestment piece is the subtle part. NPV implicitly assumes interim cash flows get reinvested at the discount rate, the WACC, which is a fair market assumption. IRR implicitly assumes you reinvest every interim cash flow at the IRR itself. If that IRR is well above your cost of capital, that is unrealistic and flatters the project. For independent projects with conventional cash flows the two rules usually agree, so I only really sweat this for mutually exclusive choices, and there I default to NPV every time.$x$),
(1771, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Multiple IRR Problem$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A mining project costs a hundred up front, generates two hundred thirty in year one, then needs a hundred thirty-two of reclamation spend in year two. Walk me through why IRR breaks here and what you would use instead.$x$, $x$["Non-Conventional Cash Flows, Two Sign Changes", "Descartes Rule, Up To Two IRRs", "Here Both Ten And Twenty Percent Set NPV To Zero", "IRR Function Can Return Misleading Single Value", "Use NPV At WACC As Decision Rule", "MIRR Resolves By Separating Finance And Reinvest Rates", "Common In Mining, Oil And Gas, Decommissioning"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The problem is the cash flow signs flip twice, minus a hundred, then plus two thirty, then minus a hundred thirty-two for reclamation. Two sign changes means by Descartes rule you can have up to two internal rates of return, and here you actually get two, ten percent and twenty percent, both of which set NPV to zero. Neither is economically meaningful on its own, and a spreadsheet IRR function will just hand you whichever root sits near its starting guess, which can mislead you badly. So I would not use IRR as the decision rule at all. I would discount the cash flows at our WACC and read the sign of the NPV, because NPV is unambiguous no matter how many times the signs change. If someone insists on a rate, I would compute the modified IRR, which assumes interim inflows reinvest at the cost of capital and outflows are financed at the financing rate, collapsing it back to a single sensible figure. This pattern is classic in mining, oil and gas, and anything with big end-of-life decommissioning costs.$x$),
(1772, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Profitability Index Rationing$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You have a fixed capex budget and more positive-NPV projects than you can fund. How do you decide what makes the cut, and where does discounted payback fit in?$x$, $x$["Capital Rationing, Constraint Is Limited Capital", "Profitability Index Equals PV Of Inflows Over Investment", "Rank By PI To Maximize NPV Per Dollar", "PI Above One Means Value-Creating", "Watch Indivisibility And Project Interactions", "Discounted Payback Is A Liquidity And Risk Screen Not Primary Rule", "Higher Rates Tighten The Budget And Raise The Bar"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Under capital rationing the constraint is dollars, not the discount rate, so I stop ranking on raw NPV and switch to bang for the buck. I compute the profitability index, the present value of a project's future cash flows divided by its upfront investment, and rank highest PI first until the budget is exhausted. A PI above one means the project creates value, and ranking by PI gets you the most total NPV per scarce dollar. I have to watch a couple of things. Projects are often indivisible, so the highest-PI set might not perfectly spend the budget and I may take a slightly lower-PI project that fits better, and I have to strip out projects that are mutually exclusive or that interact. Discounted payback I treat as a secondary screen, not the deciding rule. It tells me how long my capital is at risk on a present-value basis, which is useful for liquidity and risk, but it ignores everything after the cutoff, so I never let it override PI. In a higher-rate world the budget is tighter and the PI bar effectively rises, so discipline matters more.$x$),
(1773, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Sizing Debt To Ratios$x$, 'standard', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A company does five hundred of EBITDA and wants to raise debt while keeping a solid investment-grade profile. The agencies signal they want net leverage under three times and EBITDA interest coverage above six. How much debt can it carry, and which constraint binds?$x$, $x$["Net Leverage Test, Three Times Of Five Hundred Is Fifteen Hundred", "Coverage Test, EBITDA Over Interest Above Six", "Interest Budget Capped At Five Hundred Over Six, About Eighty-Three", "At Seven Percent Coupon Debt Capped Near Twelve Hundred", "Binding Constraint Is The Tighter One, Here Coverage", "Net Leverage Uses Debt Less Cash", "Rating Headroom And Through-Cycle EBITDA Matter"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would size against both tests and let the tighter one bind. The leverage test is easy: three times five hundred of EBITDA is fifteen hundred of net debt capacity. The coverage test is about the interest bill. They want EBITDA over interest above six, so interest is capped at five hundred divided by six, roughly eighty-three of annual interest. To turn that into a debt number I need an assumed cost. At, say, a seven percent all-in coupon, eighty-three of interest supports only about twelve hundred of debt. So coverage is the binding constraint here, not leverage, and I would size to roughly twelve hundred, not fifteen hundred. That gap is exactly why I always run both. A couple of nuances: net leverage nets cash against debt, so a big cash balance buys room on that test but not on coverage, which is driven by gross interest. And in a higher-for-longer rate environment the coverage math tightens as coupons reset, so I would stress the interest line and keep a notch of headroom to the downgrade threshold rather than sizing right to the limit.$x$),
(1774, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$FFO To Debt Lens$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$Two firms both show three times gross leverage, but one is a regulated utility and the other a cyclical industrial. Why might a rating agency assign them very different ratings, and what role do FFO-based metrics play?$x$, $x$["Gross Leverage Alone Ignores Cash Flow Quality And Volatility", "FFO To Debt Captures Cash Generation Against Debt", "FFO Is Cash Flow Before Working Capital Swings", "Business Risk And Cash Flow Stability Drive The Rating", "Utility Stable Regulated Cash Flows Support More Debt", "Cyclical Earnings Volatility Penalized At Same Leverage", "FFO Interest Coverage Complements The Leverage Picture"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Because leverage is only half the story, the agencies care just as much about the quality and stability of the cash flow servicing that debt. Gross leverage at three times treats both firms identically, but a regulated utility earns highly predictable, regulator-set cash flows, while a cyclical industrial can see EBITDA swing thirty or forty percent across a cycle. So the agency overlays business risk, and for a given leverage the volatile name gets the lower rating. FFO-based metrics are where this shows up. FFO, funds from operations, is essentially operating cash flow before working capital movements, already after cash interest and cash taxes, so FFO to debt is a cleaner read on how much real cash the business throws off against its obligations than an EBITDA multiple, because it nets out cash financing costs, taxes, and non-cash items. A utility might comfortably sit investment grade at an FFO-to-debt in the high teens, where an industrial at the same gross leverage but lumpier FFO and thinner FFO interest coverage screens weaker. So I would never rate off leverage alone; I pair it with FFO to debt and FFO interest coverage and weigh the volatility of the cash flows.$x$),
(1775, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Corporate Hedging Policy$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A board asks whether the company should hedge its FX, interest-rate, and commodity exposures. In theory shareholders can diversify these risks themselves, so build the case for when corporate hedging actually adds value and when it does not.$x$, $x$["Modigliani-Miller, Hedging Irrelevant In Frictionless Markets", "Shareholders Can Diversify Or Hedge On Own Account", "Value Comes From Reducing Costs Of Financial Distress", "Smoother Cash Flows Protect Investment And Debt Capacity", "Convex Taxes And Covenant Protection Argue For Hedging", "Hedge Exposures That Threaten Core Operations Not Speculative Bets", "Avoid Hedging To Mask Performance Or Take Views"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I would start by conceding the theory. In a frictionless Modigliani-Miller world hedging adds no value, because diversified shareholders can manage FX or rate exposure on their own account, and you are just spending money to do something they could do for free. So the case for corporate hedging has to come from real-world frictions. The biggest one is the cost of financial distress: if an unhedged commodity or currency swing can push you toward a covenant breach or a liquidity squeeze, hedging smooths cash flows and protects your ability to keep investing and to service debt through a downturn, and that has genuine value. Smoother cash flows also preserve debt capacity and can reduce expected taxes when the tax schedule is convex. The practical filter I give a board is this: hedge the exposures that, left open, could threaten the core business or your funding, especially rate risk near a refinancing, and do it to reduce volatility, not to take a view. What I would not do is hedge to smooth reported earnings cosmetically or let the treasury desk speculate; that is risk-taking dressed up as risk management.$x$),
(1776, NULL, 'primary', $x$Corporate Finance$x$, $x$Refi Wall Rate Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A company has most of its floating-rate debt maturing into a 2028 refinancing wall and is nervous about where rates and spreads land. As the corporate finance advisor, how would you manage that interest-rate and refinancing risk ahead of time?$x$, $x$["Separate Base-Rate Risk From Credit-Spread Risk", "Floating Exposure Hurts If Rates Stay Higher For Longer", "Swap Floating To Fixed Or Use Caps To Cap Base Rate", "Pre-Hedge With Forward-Starting Swaps Or Treasury Locks", "Ladder And Extend Maturities To Avoid Concentration", "Refinance Early Or Tap Private Credit For Certainty", "Spread Risk Largely Unhedgeable, Manage Via Timing And Liquidity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I would split the risk into two pieces, the base rate and the credit spread, because they are managed differently. On the base rate, floating debt into a higher-for-longer environment means rising interest cost, so I would look at swapping a chunk of that floating exposure to fixed, or buying interest-rate caps if they want to keep upside while bounding the downside. If the refinancing is a couple of years out, I can pre-hedge the rate today with forward-starting swaps or Treasury locks, so the base-rate component is fixed before I even go to market in twenty twenty-eight. On the wall itself, the real danger is concentration, so I would proactively ladder and extend maturities, refinance early when windows open rather than waiting, and consider terming out into private credit, which has expanded debt capacity and can offer execution certainty even when public markets are choppy. The honest caveat is that the credit-spread component is largely unhedgeable, so I manage that through timing, by carrying ample liquidity and an undrawn revolver, and by not letting the whole stack come due in a single year.$x$);
